fields.label_text:
RADIATOR PANEL
Cast iron and bronze
England; c. 1862

One of the few pieces of ironwork designed by Stevens for the V&A, then called the South Kensington Museum. It was made by Henry Hoole & Company of Sheffield, Yorkshire, manufacturers of metal grates and fenders, to whom Stevens was chief designer from 1850 to 1857. A contemporary photograph of the entire radiator, or 'coil-case' as it was then known, and its maker can be seen on the text panel to your right.

Museum No. A.54-1953

fields.descriptive_line: Radiator panel, cast iron and bronze, designed by Alfred Stevens, made by Henry Hoole & Company, Sheffield, ca. 1862
